ječnja 1440.","1439":"1439","Middleton, Sussex, England, United Kingdom":"Middleton, Sussex, Engleska, United Kingdom","Manchester, Lancashire, England":"Manchester, Lancashire, England","Holbrink, Kendal, Westmorland, England":"Kendal, Westmorland, England"},"cs":{"about 1420–":"okolo 1420–Zesnulý","1420–Male":"1420–Zesnulý","1420–Female":"1420–Zesnulá","1440–1519":"1440–1519","1393–1439":"1393–1439","3 July 1787":"3. července 1787","1455":"1455","1420":"1420","1440":"1440","about 1420":"okolo 1420","1393":"1393","1519":"1519","1 January 1440":"1. ledna 1440","1439":"1439","Middleton, Sussex, England, United Kingdom":"Middleton, Sussex, Anglie, United Kingdom","Manchester, Lancashire, England":"Manchester, Lancashire, Anglie","Holbrink, Kendal, Westmorland, England":"Kendal, Westmorland, Anglie"},"da":{"about 1420–":"omkring 1420–Afdød","1420–Male":"1420–Afdød","1420–Female":"1420–Afdød","1440–1519":"1440–1519","1393–1439":"1393–1439","3 July 1787":"3. juli 1787","1455":"1455","1420":"1420","1440":"1440","about 1420":"omkring 1420","1393":"1393","1519":"1519","1 January 1440":"1. januar 1440","1439":"1439","Middleton, Sussex, England, United Kingdom":"Middleton, Sussex, England, United Kingdom","Manchester, Lancashire, England":"Manchester, Lancashire, England","Holbrink, Kendal, Westmorland, England":"Kendal, Westmorland, England"},"nl":{"about 1420–":"circa 1420–Overleden","1420–Male":"1420–Overleden","1420–Female":"1420–Overleden","1440–1519":"1440–1519","1393–1439":"1393–1439","3 July 1787":"3 juli 1787","1455":"1455","1420":"1420","1440":"1440","about 1420":"circa 1420","1393":"1393","1519":"1519","1 January 1440":"1 januari 1440","1439":"1439","Middleton, Sussex, England, United Kingdom":"Middleton, Sussex, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Manchester, Lancashire, England":"Manchester, Lancashire, England","Holbrink, Kendal, Westmorland, England":"Kendal, Westmorland, England"},"en":{"about 1420–":"about 1420–Deceased","1420–Male":"1420–Deceased","1420–Female":"1420–Deceased","1440–1519":"1440–1519","1393–1439":"1393–1439","3 July 1787":"3 July 1787","1455":"1455","1420":"1420","1440":"1440","about 1420":"about 1420","1393":"1393","1519":"1519","1 January 1440":"1 January 1440","1439":"1439","Middleton, Sussex, England, United Kingdom":"Middleton, Sussex, England, United Kingdom","Manchester, Lancashire, England":"Manchester, Lancashire, England","Holbrink, Kendal, Westmorland, England":"Kendal, Westmorland, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Beswicke","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of the places in Lancashire and East Yorkshire named Beswick. The second element is Old English <i>wīc</i> ‘outlying (dairy) farm’ (see   Wick  ). The first element of the Lancashire name may be an Old English personal name <i>Bēac</i>; that of the Yorkshire name is possibly an Old Norse personal name <i>Bōsi</i> or <i>Besi</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Wick","meanings":["English: from Middle English <i>wik(e)</i> (Old English <i>wīc</i>) ‘building; enclosed piece of land; dependent farm where a certain kind of work is done’. In placenames the term is frequently combined with words associated with food production, as in Butterwick ‘butter wick’, Chiswick ‘cheese wick’, Cowick ‘cow wick’, Hardwick ‘herd wick’, Gatwick ‘goat wick’, Shapwick ‘sheep wick’, Goswick ‘goose wick’, Berwick ‘barley wick’, Fishwick ‘fish wick’. The most common sense is ‘dairy farm’. The surname may be topographic or occupational, denoting someone who lived or worked at a <i>wick</i> (compare   Wicker  ), or habitational, denoting someone who lived at or came from a place called Wick (of which there are examples in Berkshire, Gloucestershire, Somerset, Wiltshire, and Worcestershire), Wyke (Devon, Dorset, Surrey, Yorkshire), or Week (Cornwall, Devon, Hampshire, Isle of Wight, Somerset).","German: from a medieval personal name <i>Wicko</i>, a short form of any of various ancient Germanic personal names formed with the element <i>wīg</i> ‘battle, war’.","German: habitational name from Wick (Westphalia) or any of the places called Wieck or Wiek."]},{"name":"Bestwick","meanings":["English: variant of   Beswick  ."]}]},{"name":"Richard","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Rikert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]},{"name":"Rickert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":35,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Knight de la Beche Richard Beswicke was born about 1420, in Manchester, Lancashire, England as the son of Samuel Beswicke. He married Ann Morton on 3 July 1787, in Middleton, Sussex, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in his hometown."},"et":{"about 1420–":"umbes 1420–Surnud","1420–Male":"1420–Surnud","1420–Female":"1420–Surnud","1440–1519":"1440–1519","1393–1439":"1393–1439","3 July 1787":"3. juuli 1787","1455":"1455","1420":"1420","1440":"1440","about 1420":"umbes 1420","1393":"1393","1519":"1519","1 January 1440":"1. jaanuar 1440","1439":"1439","Middleton, Sussex, England, United Kingdom":"Middleton, Sussex, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Manchester, Lancashire, England":"Manchester, Lancashire, England","Holbrink, Kendal, Westmorland, England":"Kendal, Westmorland, England"},"fi":{"about 1420–":"noin 1420–Kuollut","1420–Male":"1420–Kuollut","1420–Female":"1420–Kuollut","1440–1519":"1440–1519","1393–1439":"1393–1439","3 July 1787":"3. heinäkuuta 1787","1455":"1455","1420":"1420","1440":"1440","about 1420":"noin 1420","1393":"1393","1519":"1519","1 January 1440":"1. tammikuuta 1440","1439":"1439","Middleton, Sussex, England, United Kingdom":"Middleton, Sussex, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Manchester, Lancashire, England":"Manchester, Lancashire, England","Holbrink, Kendal, Westmorland, England":"Kendal, Westmorland, England"},"fr":{"about 1420–":"environ 1420–Décédé","1420–Male":"1420–Décédé","1420–Female":"1420–Décédée","1440–1519":"1440–1519","1393–1439":"1393–1439","3 July 1787":"3 juillet 1787","1455":"1455","1420":"1420","1440":"1440","about 1420":"environ 1420","